# .cursorrules
# These rules govern ALL code generation in this project.
# Read every rule before generating any code that touches AI models,
# providers, endpoints, API calls, or the settings system.
# Phase 2 rules extend Phase 1 rules — both apply.

---

do not push to github unles requested

## ARCHITECTURE OVERVIEW

This project uses a two-layer model registry:

  LAYER 1 — config/providers.json
    Who the providers are. Static. Developer-managed.
    Contains: provider identity, capabilities, base URL,
    auth pattern, and the .env key name for their API key.

  LAYER 2 — config/models.json
    What models are available. Dynamic. User-managed via settings UI.
    Contains: model entries per capability, endpoint paths,
    request formats, response paths.

  ACTIVE — config/active_models.json
    Which model is currently selected per capability.
    Written by the settings UI General tab. Read by the resolver.

  SECRETS — .env
    API keys only. Never shown in UI. Never in JSON files.
    providers.json references the key NAME (e.g. "OPENAI_API_KEY").
    The resolver reads the value from os.getenv() at call time.

---

## RULE 1 — Never hardcode a model name, provider name, or endpoint URL

BAD:
  model="dall-e-3"
  model="gpt-4o"
  url="https://api.openai.com/v1/images/generations"

GOOD:
  model_client.call("image", prompt=prompt)
  model_client.call("llm", messages=messages)

All model names, endpoints, and request shapes live in models.json.
If you are writing a model name as a string literal in application code, stop.

---

## RULE 2 — The resolver is the only place that calls external AI APIs

File: app/services/model_client.py

Every AI API call in this project goes through model_client.call().
No other file constructs payloads, sets auth headers, or calls provider APIs.
If you are writing an HTTP call to an AI provider outside of model_client.py,
you are doing it wrong. Move the call there.

---

## RULE 3 — Resolve active model from active_models.json, never assume it

BAD:
  provider = "openai"
  model = "dall-e-3"

GOOD:
  active_id = active_selections[capability]      # from active_models.json
  model     = model_service.find(capability, active_id)   # from models.json
  provider  = provider_service.get(model["provider"])     # from providers.json

The resolver always does a three-step lookup: active → model → provider.
It never skips steps or assumes what is selected.

---

## RULE 4 — API keys come from .env via the provider's env_key field

BAD:
  api_key = "sk-abc123"
  api_key = settings.openai_key

GOOD:
  api_key = os.getenv(provider["env_key"])

The provider entry in providers.json tells the resolver which .env variable
to read. The resolver fetches it at call time. The key never appears in JSON,
code, or the settings UI.

---

## RULE 5 — Adding a new model requires only a models.json entry, no code

If a user wants to add GPT-6, a new Stability model, or any other model:
  → They click "+ Add" in the settings UI
  → They fill in the form (provider, model id, request format JSON)
  → The UI writes a new entry to models.json via the API
  → Done. Zero code changes. Zero restart required.

Never write code that needs to change when a new model is added.

---

## RULE 6 — Adding a new provider requires only a providers.json entry

If a new provider needs to be supported:
  → Add one entry to config/providers.json
  → Add their API key name to .env.example
  → Done. No new client classes. No new if/else branches. No new code.

---

## RULE 7 — The settings UI is the write layer for models and active selections

The settings page at /settings is the only place users manage:
  - Which models are available (models.json)
  - Which model is active per capability (active_models.json)

The settings UI calls the API endpoints in app/api/settings_api.py.
Those endpoints read and write the JSON files.
Nothing else writes to models.json or active_models.json.

---

## RULE 8 — The settings UI never shows or stores API keys

API keys stay in .env on the server.
The settings UI shows "Server key configured" when an env key is present.
It may allow a browser-side override key for development purposes only.
That override is stored in the browser, never sent to the server in plaintext,
and never written to any file.

---

## RULE 9 — Capability keys are fixed — use them exactly

  llm
  image
  tts
  asr
  video
  web_search
  pdf

Use these exact strings everywhere: in models.json, active_models.json,
providers.json capabilities arrays, API routes, and model_client.call() calls.
Do not invent variations.

---

## FILE REFERENCE

  config/providers.json          ← provider catalog (developer-managed)
  config/models.json             ← model list (user-managed via UI)
  config/active_models.json      ← active selection per capability (UI-managed)
  .env                           ← API keys only (never in UI or JSON)
  app/services/model_client.py   ← ONLY place that calls AI provider APIs
  app/services/provider_service.py  ← loads providers.json
  app/services/model_service.py     ← CRUD for models.json
  app/api/settings_api.py           ← API endpoints for settings UI

---

## QUICK REFERENCE — How to call each capability

  LLM:         model_client.call("llm", messages=[...])
  Image:       model_client.call("image", prompt="...")
  TTS:         model_client.call("tts", text="...", voice="...")
  ASR:         model_client.call("asr", audio_file=...)
  Web Search:  model_client.call("web_search", query="...")

---

## PHASE 1 RULES STILL APPLY

Never construct provider-specific payloads inline.
Never add provider-specific if/else branching anywhere.
Never create separate client classes per provider.
All of the original .cursorrules restrictions remain in force.